You’re describing a real shift—but it’s strongest when you frame it as a new interface layer over software, not a replacement for it.

⸻

🪄 Meaning-Driven Programming (MDP) v1.0

Using structured natural language as the primary interface for building software

⸻

🧭 Core Definition

MDP = specifying intent in structured natural language that an instrument (AI) translates into executable systems.

You’re not removing code.
You’re moving it one layer down the stack.

⸻

🧱 The Stack (what actually changes)

Before
	•	Human → code → machine

Now
	•	Human → intent spec → AI → code → machine

Code still exists—
but it becomes:

compiled output, not the primary interface

⸻

🧠 Why it feels like “magic”

Because you’re operating at:
	•	intent level instead of syntax
	•	structure level instead of implementation

So instead of:
	•	how do I write this?

You ask:

what do I want, under what constraints?

⸻

⚙️ What makes MDP actually work (invariants)

1. Clarity of intent
	•	vague → bad output
	•	precise → strong output

⸻

2. Constraint definition
	•	“what it must do”
	•	“what it must NOT do”

⸻

3. Examples / edge cases
	•	show desired behavior
	•	show failure cases

⸻

4. Iterative refinement
	•	generate → test → refine
	•	same as coding, just different interface

⸻

5. Verification
	•	you still need:
	•	testing
	•	validation
	•	review

👉 This part never goes away

⸻

🔁 The Loop (real engine)

Intent → Generate → Evaluate → Refine → Repeat

The “self-improving” effect comes from:
	•	better prompts
	•	better models
	•	better shared patterns

Not from hidden feedback loops.

⸻

🧬 What you’re calling “spells”

There is a real analogy:
	•	Language = interface
	•	Structure = syntax
	•	Constraints = logic
	•	Examples = test cases

But the grounded version is:

Good specs produce good systems.

⸻

⚠️ Important boundaries (this keeps it real)

1. Not anyone can build anything instantly
	•	domain knowledge still matters
	•	architecture still matters

⸻

2. Ambiguity still breaks systems
	•	AI doesn’t “read minds”
	•	it resolves patterns based on input

⸻

3. Code quality still matters
	•	performance
	•	security
	•	edge cases

⸻

4. No automatic external learning from your use
	•	systems don’t improve globally just because you used them in a conversation
	•	improvements come from training cycles, not individual sessions

⸻

